Contract milestones:
The specific Grinding Services to be provided are as follows:
- Main line grinding Services for all regions listed below
- Turnout grinding Services for all regions listed below
The following regions for rail grinding to be conducted is as follows
- South East Queensland (SEQ)
- North Coast Line NCL (North) - Cairns-Rockhampton
- North Coast Line NCL (Near North/South) - Parana - Tamaree
- GNR – Townsville to Mt Isa
- West Moreton System – Toowoomba to Columboola
The scope of services is to control the wheel rail interface so that rail grinding will:
- progressively establish rail profiles that optimise the wheel/rail interface condition to maximise the life of the rail and wheel asset,
- maintain rail profiles to optimise the rail/wheel interface to prevent the development of rail defects and
- remove or control existing rail surface defects and rail head metal flow.
The timeline to plan & deliver rail grinding Services shall be as outlined in the detailed Statement of Works. The stages of Services shall be planned in sufficient advance times to ensure that all of Queensland Rail’s possession planning, operational, freight business, environmental & safety requirements are timely met and also Queensland Rail’s resources are made available to support the rail grinding services delivered by the Contractor.
Contract performance management:

Grind Quality Index (GQI) or similar
Performance/Efficient Delivery of Agreed Scope
Work Free of Lost Time Injuries (LTIs)
Work free of SPADs (Signal Passed At Danger)
Administration of the Agreement

Evaluation criteria and weightings: Extension of predecessor agreement
Deliverables: Provision of Hook and Pull and Ad hoc Services for the supply of locomotives, train crew and support services for the Inlander passenger service on the Mount Isa Line, and for work trains on the Mount Isa Line and Far North Coast Line between Rockhampton and Cairns. This also incorporates ad hoc services including rollingstock recovery primarily on the Mount Isa line (recovery services are provided within the Hook and Pull Agreement on a basis of reasonable endeavours subject to availability of resources).
Contract performance management:
Both parties are equally responsible for implementing, maintaining and monitoring compliance with this ICP specifically including the risk controls as nominated.
Each Party may at a mutually convenient time and date, undertake an audit or inspection of the Services provided by each other relative to this ICP. QRL and AUR must provide one another with at least 30 calendar days' notice in writing for scheduled audits or at least 48 hours written notice for spot audits it intends to
conduct.
Instances of non-compliance must be reported and addressed by both parties to each other in a conciliatory manner that addresses the issue expediently.
Compliance with audit outcomes will be monitored through each party's internal auditing and document control processes.
Each party may, at its own cost, undertake an independent safety audit or review of another party's records of compliance with this ICP, upon giving reasonable
written notice to the other party. The parties agree to cooperate with each other in the conduct of such activity and must provide a reasonable level of cooperation (including access to documents, premises and assets) to the person/s conducting the review or audit.

Evaluation criteria and weightings: Negotiation of supply
Deliverables: Provision of Overhaul and Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) Parts
Contract performance management:
1.	Contract Program 
Where the Contract Particulars specify that a program is required, the Contractor must:
(a)	prepare and obtain Queensland Rail's approval of a program for the Supply (in a form approved by Queensland Rail) before commencing the Supply; 
(b)	at all times comply with the approved program; and
(c)	not change the program without Queensland Rail's prior written approval.

2.	Scope of the Contract
The Contractor must, as an independent contractor:
(a)	carry out the Supply; and
(b)	at the Contractor's own cost, supply all labour, materials, services, goods, plant, equipment or other things necessary to provide the Goods or Services (whether or not expressly described in the Contract) or comply with its obligations under the Contract.

3.	Laws and regulations
3.1	Compliance with the law and other requirements
The Contractor must:
(a)	comply with:
(i)	all Relevant Laws and Government Consents applicable to the Supply;
(ii)	regulations, rules, schemes or plans issued by Queensland Rail governing Site activities, industrial relations, construction, safety and the environment (including the policies referred to in section 2 of Schedule 5), and Queensland Rail's Corporate Policies applicable to the Supply; and
(b)	obtain and maintain all Government Consents in connection with the Supply; and
(c)	pay any fees, charges, levies and taxes imposed by an Authority in relation to the Supply.
The cost of complying with this clause 3.1 is included in the Contract Price. 
3.2	DDA Act compliance  
Without limiting clause 3.1, the Contractor:
(a)	acknowledges Queensland Rail is required to comply with the Disability Discrimination Act 1992 (Cth) (DDA Act); and
(b)	must ensure the Supply is compliant with the DDA Act.

4.	Quality of materials and Goods used in the Supply
All materials and Goods supplied by the Contractor must:
(a)	be of merchantable quality and fit for their intended purpose;
(b)	be free from all defects and imperfections affecting performance;
(c)	be of current manufacture, appropriate grade and suitable capacity; and 
(d)	comply with the Scope of Supply.

5.	Queensland Rail supplied materials
The Contractor must use any property, goods, materials, services or information provided by Queensland Rail:
(a)	at its own risk;
(b)	only to provide the Supply;
(c)	using reasonable care; and
(d)	in accordance with Queensland Rail's instructions.

Contract performance management:
PERFORMANCE OF WORK
1. Contract Plan
(a) The Contractor must, within 10 Business Days of the Date of Contract or as otherwise directed in writing by the Superintendent, submit to the Superintendent a plan which documents all of the systems, procedures and plans required to be implemented by the Contractor under the Contract (Contract Plan). The Contract Plan will include other plans that are required under the Contract (for example Contract Program and the Safety Management Plan or WHS Management Plan (as applicable) as those plans are finalised).
(b) The Contractor must establish, review, maintain, update and implement the Contract Plan.
(c) This clause does not limit the Contractor's obligation under this Contract to submit particular plans.
2. Contract program
2.1 Submission of Proposed Contract Program
Unless an Approved Contract Program is included in Schedule 12 at the Date of Contract, the Contractor must, within five Business Days of the Date of Contract or as otherwise directed in writing by the Superintendent, submit to the Superintendent for approval a Proposed Contract Program.
2.2 Requirements for Proposed Contract Program
A Proposed Contract Program submitted under clause E2.1 must:
(a) be prepared electronically in native file format using the format (if any) specified in the Contract or any other format required by the Superintendent;
(b) be compiled using the critical path method and show the critical path;
(c) show the start and end dates for all activities to be performed as part of the Work and milestones (if any) specified in the Scope of Work;
(d) be sufficiently detailed to enable Queensland Rail to readily evaluate the progress of the Work at any time;
(e) include an estimate of the on-Site labour requirements for, and percentage of the Work that will be completed in, each month up to the Date for Practical Completion;
(f) show work to be performed on-Site and off-Site separately; and
(g) include any further information, and comply with any format requirements, specified by the Superintendent.
2.3 Approval by Superintendent
If the Superintendent considers that the Proposed Contract Program submitted by the Contractor does not comply with clause E2.2, the Contractor must submit amendments to the Proposed Contract Program until the Proposed Contract Program is approved by the Superintendent. The Contractor must ensure that the Proposed Contract Program is in a form acceptable to the Superintendent by not later than 15 Business Days after the Date of Contract.
2.4 Compliance with Approved Contract Program
Subject to clause D1, the Contractor must not commence Work on-Site until the Superintendent has approved the Proposed Contract Program and after such approval, the Contractor must not depart from an Approved Contract Program without Queensland Rail's written consent.
2.5 Updating the Approved Contract Program
If the Superintendent grants or allows an extension of time under clause D1.7, the Contractor must submit proposed amendments to the Approved Contract Program that meets the requirements of clause E2.5 and:
(a) be accompanied by a statement of the reasons for changes from the previously submitted Approved Contract Program; and
(b) incorporate all extensions of time, which have previously been granted or allowed up to that time by the Superintendent pursuant to the Contract.
If the Superintendent considers the amended Approved Contract Program does not comply with this clause E2.5, the Contractor must submit amendments to the amended Approved Contract Program until it is approved by the Superintendent, at which time the amended Approved Contract Program will become the Approved Contract Program.
2.6 Reporting on Progress
Within 5 days of the end of each month, the Contractor must provide the Superintendent with a report of the progress of the Work against the Approved Contract Program.
This report must:
(a) contain the same information as in the Approved Contract Program;
(b) be based on information current at the time of the submission; and
(c) show the 'as-built' Approved Contract Program in respect of all Work performed to the time of the report.
Where required by the Superintendent, the Contractor and the Superintendent will meet to review the progress report.
2.7 Other obligations
The provision of a Proposed Contract Program or an amended Proposed Contract Program does not relieve the Contractor of any obligations under the Contract, including the obligation not to depart from an earlier Approved Contract Program without Queensland Rail's consent.
2.8 Costs
The Contractor must bear all costs incurred in the preparation, submission and amendment of a Proposed Contract Program, and in updating and reporting on, and reviewing, an Approved Contract Program.

Contract description/name: 2019 AUCHENFLOWER AND CANNON HILL STATION ACCESSIBILITY UPGRADES
Evaluation criteria and weightings:
Quality of design management resources - 10%
Quality of project management team - 15%
Resourcing and depth of alternate resources for key positions - 7%
Project appreciation methodology constructability - 15%
Experience - 15%
Schedule - detailed integrated program of works - 10%
Risk identification and mitigation strategy - 5%
Local content and social procurement - 3%
Price - 20%
Deliverables:
Auchenflower and Cannon Hill Stations are part of a rolling program of accessibility upgrades being delivered by Queensland Rail with the aim of improving accessibility at several stations across the Southeast Queensland (SEQ) network. 
The projects' objective is to make the station independently accessible along the primary path of travel (PPT), ensuring compliance with all relevant codes and standards. 
Improvements to the stations include a new footbridge and lifts, high level platforms to provide easier access where the assisted boarding point is located, and extended waiting shelters. The upgrade also includes a range of other accessibility features such as hearing augmentation loops, wayfinding information and signage, improved lighting, and security.
Contract milestones:
Possession of Site is given on and from 02 July 2020 (Auchenflower) and 17 July 2020 (Cannon Hill), (or as directed by the Superintendent) and provided all contractual obligations that are prerequisite to the commencement of Works have been met to the satisfaction and acceptance of the Superintendent. The Date for Practical Completion for each Separable Portion is as follows:
•	Separable Portion 1 Auchenflower - 13 April 2022
•	Separable Portion 2 Cannon Hill - 21 September 2021
Contract performance management:
The Contractor shall carry out and complete works under contract in accordance with the Contract and Directions authorised by the Contract.
The Principal shall pay the Contractor:
a) for work for which the Principal accepted a lump sum, the lump sum; and
b) for work for which the Principal accepted rates, the sum of the products ascertained by multiplying the measured quantity of each section or item of work actually carried out under the Contract by the rate accepted by the Principal for the section or item, adjusted by any additions or deductions made pursuant to the Contract.
